{{More citations needed|date=February 2014}} {{Infobox musical artist | name = Awalmir | native_name = {{Lang|ps|استاد اولمیر}} | background = solo_singer | image = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth-date|1931}} | birth_place = Charsada, Pakistan | death_date = {{death-date|April 24, 1982}} (aged 50-51) | death_place = [[Kabul]], [[Afghanistan]] | genre = [[Ghazals]]{{-}}[[Classical music]] | occupation = Singer | instrument = [[Pump organ|Harmonium]], [[guitar]] | years_active = 1949 – 1982 | label = Various }}
'''Ustad Awalmir''' ({{lang-ps|'''استاد اولمیر'''}}) (born 1931 in [[Logar Province|Logar]], [[Afghanistan]] – died April 24, 1982 in [[Kabul]], Afghanistan) was an ethnic [[Pashtuns|Pashtun]] [[Afghan]] [[composer]], musician, singer, and [[poet]] who wrote and sang in the [[Pashto language]].
He began learning music as a teen from various music teachers and began to perform for [[radio]] broadcasts. His first song was ''My Heart Has Broken To Pieces''. At the age of 18, he performed at the [[Afghan Independence Day]] in Kabul.
He made a breakthrough into performing on the [[List of radio stations in Afghanistan|Afghan radio station]] with help from [[Malang Jan]], a local poet. Awalmir's output consists of over 250 songs as well as a collection of self-composed songs. His contribution to Afghan music led him the honor of the title [[Ustad]] from the [[Ministry of Information and Culture (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Culture and Information]].
His love and patriotism for Afghanistan is demonstrated in songs such as the famous "Da Zamong Zeba Watan", meaning "this is our beautiful homeland", referring to Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.virtualafghans.com/music/awal_mir/watan/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-02-02 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203124142/http://www.virtualafghans.com/music/awal_mir/watan/ |archivedate=2014-02-03 |df= }}</ref>
